The paper deals with graph theory and the characterization of graph classes, which suggests that it could belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) category. The concept of pairwise compatibility graphs is a geometric one, and the paper uses an edge-weighted tree to define the class, which could also place it in the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) category. The paper also discusses the properties of graphs and their intersections with the PCG class, which could make it relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. The paper uses a new proof technique to show that certain graph classes are not PCGs, which could make it relevant to the Graph Theory (cs.GT) category. Finally, the paper could also be relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category, as pairwise compatibility graphs have applications in modeling social networks.
